1. Introduction:
-----------------
      * It is a standard markup language used to create web pages. 
      * Basic Skeleton of web page.
      * Basic building block of web page.
      * It follows standard w3c (world wide web consortium).
      * Not case sensitive.

      * It stands for "HyperText Markup Language". 
          * HyperText -----------------> It means one page is linked with many other pages.
          * Markup    -----------------> Combinations of <tags>.
          * Language  -----------------> which follows certain set of rules/guidelines.

      * HTML docs can be opened in two ways:-
          * usig text editor
          * using browser




















2. Comment:
------------
      * single/multi-line:  <!--     -->
      * vs code shortcut:   ctrl + /




















3. Structure of html:
----------------------
      * ! + Enter    (shortcut in VS code to get below Ammet Abbreviation) 
     
      <!DOCTYPE html>
      <html lang="en"> 
      <head> 
          <meta charset="UTF-8">                                                         
          <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
          <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
          <title> </title>
          <link rel=" " type=" " >
          <script></script>
          <style></style>
      </head>
      <body></body>
      </html>




















4. Meaning of html structure:
------------------------------
      * <!DOCTYPE html>          :- It tells browser that this document is an HTML5 document.
      * <html>                   :- It is a root of html page.
      * <html lang="en"          :- It tells content of web page is in English.
      * <head>                   :- It contains metadata (data about data) that describes main content of web page.
      * <meta attribute="value"> :- Tell the browser to parse the markup into multiple languages by creating a meta element as a child of the head element.
      * <meta charset="UTF-8">   :- It tells the browser how to encode characters for the page. It includes most characters from the majority of written languages.
      * <title>                  :- It specifies a title for web page which is shown in the browser title bar.
      * <body>                   :- It contains the actual content which are visible to us.




















5. Tags:
---------
      * It's an anonymous notation that tells browser how to render different element.
      * Tags are emclosed in < > brackets.
        <p>   :- Paragraph Tag
        <br/> :- Line Break Tag
        <hr/> :- Horizontal row
        
      * Types of Tags:
            1) Empty Tags/self closing tag ---------> Tags without closing tags are known as Empty tags. Ex- <img />, <br />, <hr />, <input />, etc.
            2) Non-Empty Tags




















6. Html Elements:
------------------
      * It is defined as [ Opening Tag + Content + Closing Tag (optional)]
        Ex:-  <h1> My First web page </h1>                     ---------------> Element
        Ex:-  <img src = "wallpaper.jpg"  alt="Loading..." />  ---------------> Void Element
                    |           |
                    |           |
                 Attribute    Value    
                    or
                 Property




















7. Types of Element:
---------------------
      * Inline element:-
            * An inline element does not start on a new line.
            * An inline element only takes up as much width as necessary.
            * Inline elements don't have top and bottom margins.
            	Ex- <em>, <button>, <span>, <br>, etc.
              
      * Block level element:-
            * A block-level element always starts on a new line, and the browsers automatically add some space (a margin) before and after the element.
            * A block-level element always takes up the full width available.
            * Block element have both top and bottom margins.
              Ex- <div>, <p>, <h1>, etc.




















8. Attribute/Property:
-----------------------
      * HTML attributes are special words used inside the opening tag of an element to control the element's behavior.
      * All html elements can have attributes.
      * Attribute provide additional information about elements.
      * Attribute always come with name-value pair.
      * Ex:- <p title="I'm a tooltip"> This is a paragraph </p>




















9. Style Attribute:
--------------------
      * style attribute is used to add styles to an element such as- color,font,size,etc.
      * syntax: <tagname style="property:value;"> </tagname>   ------> Also called inline-style.




















10. Heading Tag:
-----------------
      * <h1> </h1> :- Largest size
      * <h2> </h2>
      * <h3> </h3>
      * <h4> </h4>
      * <h5> </h5>
      * <h6> </h6> :- Smallest size




















11. Formatting Tags:
---------------------
      * <b>       :- Bold text
      * <em>      :- Emphasized text  ✔ 
      * <strong>  :- Important text  ✔ 
      * <i>       :- Italic Text
      * <mark>    :- Marked text
      * <small>   :- smaller text
      * <del>     :- Deleted text
      * <ins>     :- Inserted text
      * <u>       :- Underlined text
      * <big>     :- Bigger text
      * <sub>     :- subscript text   (H2O)
      * <sup>     :- superscript text (x^2 + x^2) 
      * <pre>     :- pre-formatted text  (poet problem (all content inside it get displayed as it is)).




















12. Image Tag:
---------------
      * It can improve the design and appearance of a web page.
      * <img src="URL" alt=" " width=" " height=" " border=" " />
      * The alt attribute's text is used for screen readers to improve accessibility and is displayed if the image fails to load. 
      * <figure>
            <img />
            <figcaption> </figcaption>
        </figure>
        
      * <picture>
            <source srcset=""> </source>
            <source srcset=""> </source>
        </picture>
        
      * <img src=" " usemap="#abcd"> ------------------------> Refer to W3School.com
            <map name="abcd">
            <area shape="" coords="" href="">
        </map>




















13. Favicon:
-------------
      * It is a small image displayed next to the page title in the browser tab.
      * syntax:
        <head>
            <link rel="icon" type="image/x-icon" href="image.png" />
        </head>




















14. Quotation & Citation Tag:
------------------------------
      * <blockquote> :- It defines a section that is quoted from another section. Browsers usually indent <blockquote> elements.
      * <q>          :- It defines short quoteations (" ")
      * <address>    :- It defines the contact information for the author of the documents.
                        Usually the content inside are rendered in "itallic".
                  
      * <cite>       :- It defines the title of a creative work (e.g. a book, a poem, a song, a movie, a painting, a sculpture, etc.).
                        Ex- <p> <cite> written by </cite> <cite> - Sachin Kumar </p>
                        
      * <bdo>        :- It defines the text direction.
      
      * <abbr title="Hyper Text Markup Language"> HTML </abbr> :- It defines Abbreviation or Acronym.




















15. Lists:
-----------
      * It allows to group a set of related items in lists.
      * Ordered List: 
            <ol type="">
                <li> Item-1 </li>
                <li> Item-2 </li>
            </ol>
            
       * Unordered list:
            <ul type="">
                <li> Item-1 </li>
                <li> Item-2 </li>
            </ul>
            
       * Description List: 
            * It is a list of terms with a description of each items.
            * The <dl> tag defines the description list, the <dt> tag defines the term (name), and the <dd> tag describes each term:
              <dl>
                <dt> Coffee </dt>
                <dd> -Black Hot drink </dd>
              </dl>




















